In a #small pot{}, combine @bulgur wheat{1/2%cup}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @water{1%cup}, @harissa powder{1/2%tsp} (you'll use more later), and @salt{1/2%tsp}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until water has absorbed and bulgur is tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in step 4.

While bulgur cooks, wash and dry produce.

Trim and finely dice @Persian cucumber{1}(finely diced). Finely dice @Roma tomato{1}(finely diced). Pick and mince fronds from @dill{1/4%ounce}(minced).

Pat @chicken breast strips{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season with @Tunisian spice blend{1%tbsp}, @harissa powder{1%tsp} (be sure to measure), and a big pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. 

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add chicken in a single layer; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Drain any excess liquid from bulgur if necessary. Stir in @butter{1/2%tbsp} until melted. Transfer to a #large bowl{} along with cucumber, tomato, half the @feta cheese{1/4%cup}, and minced dill to taste (start with half and add more from there if desired). Toss with half the @Greek vinaigrette{3/4%oz}. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide tabbouleh between #bowls{} and top with harissa chicken. Top with remaining @Greek vinaigrette{3/4%oz} and remaining feta. Serve.

> For 4 servings, use 2 cups water and 1 tsp harissa powder; we used 1 tsp salt and 1 TBSP butter. Use remaining harissa powder for 4 servings total.